Oct 3 2009 	Good Hotel	Overall, a fairly good hotel that comes with all the amenities. It's a bit on the small side so I wouldn't encourage an extended stay here. Most likely, this is the kind of place for business class travelers and long weekends. Classy hotel offers all the basic amenities that come in a hotel room such as complimentary toiletries and what have you. This hotel certainly showcases it's history and obviously hasn't lost it's identity or style, while still managing to retain a contemporary image. Gorgeous hotel lobby is awe inspiring to say the least when you walk in, making you feel as if you're walking into the gold plated interior of a mansion. Service is relatively solid from the staff and all my needs were addressed, complete with a complimentary newspaper at my door. Hotel rooms are small and I had stayed in a single, but enjoyed what the place had to offer. Bathroom is definitely meant for one individual and surprisingly, it's a bathroom that's held up over decades of use as the Drake is kind of a local institution. Now speaking as a guy, I have absolutely no credibility in terms of interior design but I did enjoy the room interior: green and white striped walls that add to a fairly reassuring and comforting feel to the room, which comes with both TV, DVD player and overpriced video rentals. As far the area itself, the Drake is right in San Francisco's Union Square, a tourist mecca full of all the big name retail stores you know: Neiman Marcus, Macy's, Borders, Gap and Victoria's Secret. It also has the convenience of being across the street from a Walgreen's for all your basic needs. But as I said, this is the place for a short stay as opposed to a long one. So if you need groceries, you'll need public transportation to get to a supermarket. But overall, this is a relatively solid hotel and I would highly recommend staying here.	
