Aug 22 2009 	Thanks to the Swine Flu Scare a 24-hour room sale was too hard to resist...	This was my wife's and my first anniversary so we wanted to have a romantic getaway in San Francisco. Yes, as many others have posted on TripAdvisor and elsewhere, the Sir Francis Drake is a historical downtown hotel, meaning small rooms and dated decor. But its location and great staff made it a pleasure to stay 4 nights exploring Union Square, Chinatown, Fisherman's Wharf and Golden Gate Park.As a mature couple on a budget, staying in a good hotel is a balance between location, amenities, service AND price. However, with the economy still on a downturn AND possibly the Swine Flu scare earlier this year (Spring 2009), this Klimton Hotel had a 24-hour sale too hard to resist! Our room was 65% off! That saving can pay for tons of hand sanitizers...And thanks to previous TripAdvisor reviews, we paid an extra $20/night to get a Queen size room in the Tower. It seems that some of the rooms are in the old 6 storey section of the hotel, meaning quite close to the street noise, etc. Those higher up in the tower not only get a view, but more distance from the street noise (especially in the downtown Union Square area!).I mentioned that the staff were great, from the costumed doorman who greeted us and helped with our luggage... to the check-in staff who chose us a great room on the 18th floor away from the front street, with a view into the surrounding streets, etc. ... to the housecleaning staff... The conceirge was especially helpful, even if she was busy with everyone asking her the usual touriste questions, etc.The free wireless Internet in the lobby and rooms worked well, although it could be slow sometimes. The only complaint that we had was the sticky bathroom window. Being an old hotel, it still has wooden sliding windows so if you wanted to vent the steam and moisture from the shower, you need to open the window... even the few inches allowed from the bottom. But opening the window could be a challenge if you aren't strong or stubborn enough: the wooden frame needs lubrication... and slides closed again overnight.Finally, if you are thinking of taking the BART from SFO to this Union Square hotel... it might be better to take a shuttle service. BART now costs $8.10 each from the Airport to the Union Square station, then a 4+ block walk uphill in places to the Sir Francis Drake hotel. My wife and I decided to use the shuttle service reserved for us by the conceige the day before our departure. It was well worth the $17 each for door-to-door shuttle service. In fact, since we were going to rent a car from the airport for the next part of our vacation, it was worth tipping the shuttle driver who took us directly to the actual car rental area next to the airport.As noted elsewhere, parking in downtown San Francisco can be expensive: this hotel charges $48day for parking. Other hotels charge $55 to $58... that's why we didn't rent a car for our trip until we were going elsewhere (Silicon Valley and Monterey) afterwards.	
