Mar 20 2009 	Beautiful hotel in great location - a bit rough around the edges	My wife and I stayed at the Sir Francis Drake because she had a conference that was hosted their. I tagged along and we made a long weekend of it. As most of the other reviewers note, this is a charming place. I'm really happy that historic places like this still exist and that we can stay in them. Our room was not at all tiny. It was immaculately clean. The beds were super comfy and the decor was really really cool. You don't feel compelled to take pictures of your room at most hotels - at least most of the places we stay at. Our room at the SF Drake was that cool.I see another reviewer mention that he got a coffee machine sent up. I wish I would have read that before we stayed. Our room had no coffee maker and we are marginally addicted to coffee. It seemed odd at the time and as small a thing as that is, it was a drag to have to trek downstairs and around the corner to the [evil national coffee chain with great coffee] and fork over cash for coffee. What kind of hotel does not even have a pot of coffee in the lobby? The other horrifying experience was on the Saturday night of our stay. The guests next door decided to have a small party - the noises of which flowed directly into our room. Now this is a *highly* crappy situation. We were exhausted from a hard day of being tourists, but sleeping with that going on was impossible. We are hardly &quot;light sleepers&quot; as we live in Chicago near the el and on a rather busy street. Anyway, after trying to ignore it for as long as we could we finally called the front desk to register a complaint. I feel like a complete jerk doing something like that, but I was tired and crabby and probably out-numbered so I was not about to do the human thing and confront our neighbors about it personally. Minutes go by, an hour - nothing changed. I call again and then about 30 min later things quiet down next door. I may be spoiled, but that sort of thing is a huge drag. I realize that a hotel can't know who is gonna do what in their rooms, but once a situation like that is brought to their attention it should be resolved more or less immediately, not an hour and a half later. And if it does take that long to resolve at least some kind of gesture of apology is in order.Those two small factors weighed pretty heavily in my decision to give this place an overall rating of &quot;Average&quot; it is really an above average hotel with an above average number of both charms and flaws.	
