Feb 16 2009 	Excellent hotel and great location	Stayed here for a week in July 2008, primary reason for being in SFO was a business trip but stayed on with my wife to see the city. Location is great - just a block off Union Square - and it's very good value for this area. San Francisco is a terrific city with loads to do and the concierge was very helpful. The Starlight room is on the top floor - just find out what's on each night and you're likely to find something you like. Just across the road is a great little place for breakfast called Sears (famous for pancakes), It's well worth a visit even if you have to queue which is the norm during busy periods. The Hotel bar is simple and small but the barman makes a good cocktail and there is also an italian restaurant attached to the hotel (separately run I think). The room - a Tower Queen room which we were upgraded to by the manager (a thorough professional) was of ample size and very comfortable - however the bathroom was small with limited storage space, but that did not bother us. Altogether a great experience and we would return to the SFD again. By the way - if you're planning on walking and sightseeing, we found the weekly travel pass very useful and great value (unlimited rides on Bart, F, Trolley car). Although Fisherman's wharf is not idea of a day out, it's worth taking the trolley there and having an Irish Coffee in The Buena Vista. And for the Italian touch with the great sense of cultural history, try an Espresso at Cafe Trieste on 601 Vallejo Street.	
Jan 29 2009 	Insufferable noise incompetent staff	My experience was very similar to RoColorado's (1/19/09 review) - I was attending a meeting at the hotel so I stayed there, found a friendly checkin staff, nice lobby, and shabby, cramped, business-unfriendly, unbelievably noisy room. I'd asked at checkin if there was a coffeemaker in the room, and when the checkin clerk said there was not, I requested one. Housekeeping brought it up quickly, but it was an ancient model that looked like it had not been cleaned in months. (Cloudy decanter, coffee stains all over the device, etc.) Then I noticed that they'd only brought two packs of decaf, so I had to call down again to Housekeeping for regular coffee. This time it took them about half an hour to bring. And no place in the room to put the coffeemaker with a plug accessible to the short cord.The next problem - discovering that there was no wireless reception in the room for internet connection, and no wall cable connection for backup. Another call to the front desk, and they say they'll send up a signal booster device to connect. A half hour for this delivery also; and the staff guy who delivered the device (right on the footsteps of the Housekeeping guy with the coffee) apologized that he &quot;hadn't been trained in how to use it&quot; so he couldn't explain it but could send up an engineer. Never mind the engineer, the wireless still didn't work even with the booster device. Net result: no internet service, no ability for me to work. Those two experiences already turned me against the place, but what moves this review irretrievably to one star was the unbearable, inexcusable noise.I was in room 1116, a corner room on the 11th floor. The building directly across Sutter Street was being remodeled or rebuilt or something. There was construction work going on literally all night: a crane parked at the corner of Powell and Sutter, digging and banging and beeping and pounding, workers yelling, all until 3:45 a.m. It would have been impossible to sleep while that was going on unless I was dead drunk, which I was not; I could not get to sleep until 4 a.m. The management response to RoColorado's complaint about the same thing would be a joke if it wasn't a lie. This was not traffic noise, cable cars, or the &quot;general excitement of the city.&quot; It was a 50-foot crane doing heavy construction work, including posthole digging, overnight from 11 p.m. to 4 a.m., RIGHT UNDER MY WINDOW. The hotel must have known this work was going on, and should have warned me of the noise and offered a different room even if it was at a different rate. That they did not is inexcusable.I can't remember a worse noise experience in decades of business and pleasure travel. The age and history of the hotel is no excuse: there are plenty of hotels in SF that combine age and character with business-friendly rooms, the Palace where I stay frequently being an obvious example, and that's without even mentioning the more modern chain hotels that are better equipped with desk furniture, electric and internet outlets, and of course soundproof rooms. Sorry, Drake, you fail.	
