Aug 25 2008 	Excellent Stay at the Sir Francis Drake Hotel	Let me start by saying that I'm the cynical type, so if I write something nice about a stay, the place just might be worth a look . . . If you are seeking a grand hotel, a smaller version of New York's Plaza Hotel, then you've come to the right place. With a location in the Union Square district, it is just about as central as you could want to be. They've spent a lot of effort overhauling this building and it shows; just the right combination of old marble and new interior design. Transportation: outside is the cable car, though you should walk a couple of blocks down the hill to catch it, because it's filled to the brim with tourists by the time it passes the hotel. Go a couple of blocks further down the hill and catch the underground. Secret: To get to fisherman's wharf/alcatraz, if you get fed up waiting for the cable car, hit the underground; take it out to the embarcadero/ferry building and then take a trolley along the waterfront to the wharf. A lot less crowded . . . On the return, retrace your steps but at the Ferry Building, walk toward the subway and take the OTHER (Powell/Hyde?) cable car back home, since its not crowded. Get a map from the concierge and you'll get the picture.Shopping: One door down is Saks Fifth Ave. Turn the corner and you are in the shopping district if that is your thing. It's much denser shopping than New York; you get every brand on top of each other in a few blocks.Amenities: Rooms are recently upgraded and it shows. Comfortable and quiet. The staff are exceedingly helpful. A concierge and doorman who actually know the town well and have a great attitude.The lobby is seriously cool. With a two-story ceiling, nice arrangement of sofas, chairs, and a bar, its not too big, just about right. Tourist Attractions: You can easily walk to Chinatown and the City Lights bookstore. For points beyond, the hills can be a challenge; buses are plentiful. Get a 3 day pass down the block across from Macy's. You can buy half price theatre tickets there too. Eating: Streetlevel is leased to Starbucks and an upscale restaurant. We ventured a few blocks out and there are loads of places to eat. If we saw a mob of tourists, we just moved on. There are very few bad choices as far as eating in that area. Oh yes, and if you want to get snacks for the room, go across the street to Walgreens, which seems to be open all night. Photos: I google streetviewed this place and it looks small from the outside, but isn't. They've wisely leased their frontage space to the starbucks and scala's restuarant. Actually, the hotel covers half the block. In closing, a really great place to hang your hat while you're staying in San Fran.	
