Aug 5 2008 	Won't be going back to the Sir Francis Drake	I left the Sir Francis Drake unhappy, and would not go back. I will start with the basics; room size was fine, with a good walk in closet and nice toiletries in the bath. But there was only one chair, a rolling computer desk chair. The bath towels were coarse, the only towel rods were inside the bath tub. A tiny shelf over the toilet was the only dry place to sit anything. The vanity, a large boxy useless thing, had no shelves or door. The bathroom door wouldn't close. The room had AC, but it was as loud as my window AC unit at home. As it cycled on and off it would wake me up. All of these points my husband and I would've overlooked, if we had not had a bad night during our stay. The SFD was hosting a wedding reception our first night. Some of the guests appeared to be staying on our floor . After 1 AM we were awoken by drunken people coming off the elevator cursing at the top of their lungs. My husband got up, opened the door a bit and told the people to keep their voices down. A young man, in a tux, cursed at my husband and kicked our door in. My husband slammed the door shut and called the front desk to report the incident. Later we spotted someone who looked like security walking the floor. It took a long time to get to sleep after that excitement. The next morning we realized the chain lock had been broken and the door was scratched. So we reported it to a young lady at the front desk on our way out to breakfast. The front desk had not heard about the incident from the night staff, so we repeated the report. The clerk apologized and offered to move us. We declined that offer and asked that they fix the lock. The clerk also walked around the corner and told a 'manager' what had happened, I heard her. By the time we got back from breakfast the lock was repaired. That was the last we heard from hotel management while we were there. The incident wasn't the hotel's fault, but the control of guests at hotel receptions is their responsibility. I expected a Manager would contact us at some point during our stay to check on us but no more mention was made, even when we checked out. It left a bad taste in my mouth. I canceled the one night we had booked for a week later. When I got home a full week after our stay at the SFD, there was a survey from Kimpton waiting on my computer. I completed it, in full detail. Two days later a Manager from the Sir Francis Drake called me. He had never heard about the incident, not after our 2 reports to staff and the repaired door lock. He apologized and explained that even though the wedding party had spent around $20,000 at the hotel, that didn't give them the right to disturb other guests. I agree with him on that. He also said he would tell the hotel catering group. But its a shame that I had to fill out a post occupancy survey to get a Manager's attention. We are not ones to make a stink, but being nice quiet guests doesn't get you anywhere. We were just a couple of tourists staying for a couple of nights. Obviously we ranked far below a pricey wedding reception. The SFD didn't go that extra distance for us. There are other places to stay in San Francisco where we would be treated with more concern, we won't bother with the SFD again.	
