Jul 29 2008 	An Updated Classic	In the busy heart of Union Square, the Sir Francis Drake is a dowager recently transformed into a boutique hotel. Don't expect large corporate &quot;business-class&quot; rooms or a spacious resort. Do expect roomy-enough sleeping areas, deiiciously comfortable new beds and furnishings, and pocket-sized, yet modern bathrooms. I'm a native San Franciscan and remember the SFD as a touristy hotel that also drew ladies who went to town on shopping vacations. I stayed here in July 2008 while visiting family in the City who have tiny apartments without room for me to sleep (typical SF).I was pleased with the comfort of the place: chummy helpful doormen dressed as London Beefeaters, a cozy, ornate,&quot;clubby&quot; lobby with a creative bar (try the SFD bartender's recently invented Tommy Gun cocktail $9), and freshly designed rooms. Scala's Restaurant on the premises is very good - nicely done steaks and pastas in a happy 1920's setting.We reserved a room via hotels.com for an unheard of price (1/5 the &quot;retail&quot; rate listed on the placard in the room!). Of course prices are subject to change. We also got this fantastic room (#425) due to a snafu on the day we arrived. The central computers at Kimpton Seattle went down and the beleaguered, yet professionally good-natured staff went room by room with the housekeepers and clipboards to see which rooms were vacated and ready.I don't think we were intended to be in this room, but we took it :-)Note that this hotel, like most in Union Square was on the corner of busy Powell and Sutter Streets, so street noises are the norm. We were on Powell St and heard the ding-ding of the cable cars going into the night - nice. The first night there was city sewer construction all night (!), but that was one night. if you want relative quiet, ask for an inner albeit darker room. Our triple layered curtains blocked out all light, and muffled some noise, too.Note also that the popular Starlight Room is on the 21st floor, so I'd avoid staying in rooms on the two or three floors directly under that, since the disco beat will permeate down.Do know that Powell Street/Union Square is crazy busy. It's teeming with traffic and people and noise. I'd been used to staying in quieter neighborhoods of SF (Castro, Sunset, Richmond) in the past and had forgotten about this chaotic, touristy part of the City. The first few moments i arrived I absolutely hated it and thought I'd made a terrible mistake, but I got used to it. It is fun to see all the humanity in a few square blocks!SF is all about enjoying street life, like Europe, so you really don't need a huge impersonal hotel room to knock around in. Your room is a place to rest before going out again and gain to enjoy the City.	
Jul 29 2008 	Functional stay for non-representing conference visitors	San Francisco is similar to many European cities, but still not. The Sir Francis Drake hotel represents some of those typical differences by being an unusually large and anonymous hotel. The hotel is however perfectly functional, as expected and desired for this particular trip. A surprisingly small room compared to other US hotels I have stayed at, priced only slightly lower vs competition. The helpful and service-minded staff was highly appreciated. The hotel is centrally - and safely - located, with excellent shuttle bus connections to the Moscone congress centre and to the tourist parts of the city. The location guarantees nearby quality shopping and many reasonable restaurants for all your meals. Strikingly similar to the neighbouring hotel Westin St Francis. My recommendation is to confidently book either of them for a short, practical congress stay without required representation. The Ritz Carlton or Fairmont qualify better for the last part, however bear in mind then the cost will also be very different.	
