Jul 15 2008 	Getting older not better	I stayed in the SF Drake on business for three days. I understand that the hotel is “a classic” and tried to give it the benefit of the doubt, but ultimately, it turned out to be a hotel I wouldn't recommend.  In the heart of downtown San Francisco, the SF Drake is only a couple blocks from Union Square and Chinatown, and maybe a 15 minute cable-car ride from Fisherman’s Wharf. The cable-car stop is right outside the hotel’s front door, which is very convenient. The hotel is “old” in more of a classic sense than a &quot;run-down&quot; sense. But once you get past the impressive décor of the lobby, it really doesn’t offer anything exceptional in the way of comfort, amenities, or even ambiance.  Our room was an “inside” room on the sixth floor, which means we had a view of the back of another building and, as a result, were subjected to the constant drone of the ventilation/air-conditioning system. This wasn’t a big problem, but it was like having a bathroom fan going constantly. It was one of the smallest hotel rooms I’d ever stayed in. There was one small set of three drawers to store clothes, which was fine for three nights, but would have been difficult during a longer stay. At $158 per night (including tax) it was reasonably priced, but the age and the set-up of the rooms made it difficult to enjoy.  The room had various minor problems with it. The bathroom door wouldn’t close properly, which would have been fine, except that it would gradually drift open and had to be propped closed from the outside. The towel rack was starting to come out of its wall anchors, which gave the room a bit of a run-down look. In addition, the ice machine on our floor and the floor above did not work, so I was up two floors before I found one that did work. I was also disappointed by the hotel’s business center and internet service. On our last night, I asked whether there was somewhere I could check-in on-line for my flight home and print out boarding passes. They directed me to their business center. Not only did they charge $6 for 15 minutes of internet access, but they also charged for printing pages. The first two pages printed fine. But after I sent my third and fourth pages to the printer, I received a pop-up message indicating that I would be charged another dollar or so. The hotel’s wireless internet (which I accessed in my room) worked fine, but it is a pet peeve of mine that some hotels charge a daily fee for access. As a hotel guest, I shouldn’t expect to be charged for internet access any more than I should expect to be charged for towels or shampoo.  The SF Drake holds itself up as a classy, classic hotel. Unfortunately, it is becoming very close to being simply an old hotel. Despite the great location and the good price, I would probably look for somewhere else to stay next time.	
