Jun 4 2008 	Beautiful lobby great location but hit or miss with the rooms	This was my second stay at the Sir Francis Drake, having stayed here in March 2008. My group was placed at the hotel by the housing bureau of the conference we were attending. The hotel's location is perfect for those wanting to get the feel of San Francisco. Close to the convention center, right in Union Square, with Chinatown only a few blocks away. For those who love to shop, there are plenty of stores.The doormen are dressed in costume and are quick to help with luggage and hailing taxis. The bellman are efficient and quick to point out the features of the room as well as where the ice machine and fire exits are.Check in was smooth and effortless, even when I forgot my Kimpton rewards number. The staff member kindly looked it up and added it to my reservation. The lobby of the hotel is magnificent, with high ceilings, comfortable sofas and chairs, and a nicely stocked bar. Aaron, one of the bartenders, is delightful and charming as well as creative. He was mixing up new drinks and explaining to the patrons the different tastes he was going for. There were a few of us there on business, so it was nice to have an engaging bartender. The elevators are small but relatively quick. During my first stay in March, I was on the 10th floor and had a decently sized room. The TV was on the dresser at the foot of the bed, so viewing wasn't an issue. The bathroom, however, was very small with little storage space for my toiletries. For a one-night stay, that's OK, but for the May trip, I was there for 7 days, so the lack of space became tedious.The bath amenities are Aveda products, which are my personal favorites. The tub is deep and the shower had good water pressure. For my second stay in May, I was on the 7th floor, close to the elevator. My room was tricky to get to, since it was tucked away in a side hall. The space was considerably smaller -- reminding me of a European hotel room -- and the TV was on the dresser that was parallel to the bed. Yes, viewing was a bit of a pain in the evening but it wasn't too bad.The real eyesore in the room was the left-over in-window AC/heating unit. The Sir Francis Drake now has central heating/air with individual temperature controls. While I didn't have a problem with mine, several of my colleagues complained that their AC didn't work. It, of course, had to be a freakish heatwave that hit in May, with temperatures well into the high 90's. Kudos for complimentary wireless internet access, but my telephone didn't work even after maintenance repaired it once. It's hard to order room service when the only phone in the room doesn't work.The business center is located in the lobby and has two pay-per-use computers. Unfortunately, the first computer I tried to use wouldn't recognize my memory stick and the printer connect to the second one constantly jammed. Of course, I was trying to print out documents for a meeting that was starting in 15 minutes. Three cheers for Elgin at the front desk, who tried to fix the printer and the understanding that I was under the gun, took the memory stick, printed the file and made the number of copies I needed. Because I had so much trouble with the machines, he didn't charge me for the copies. So... while my coworkers' experiences were particularly good, I didn't have problems with my room (except that the bathroom had no storage). It seems that it all depends on the luck of the draw with rooms. You'll either get one that has a decent amount of space or one that's cramped with things that don't quite work. Regardless, it is a beautiful hotel and I'm willing to stay here again as long as Aaron's at the bar and Elgin's behind the front desk.	
Jun 4 2008 	a great value and exceptional service -- one of the best in the city!	The Sir Francis Drake is managed by the Kimpton group and reflects that company's high standards of service. As with most downtown lodging, it is a *hotel* and not a *resort* in the comptemporary sense of the latter. That being said, there are a number of resort-like amenities available -- such as the spa, fitness center and business center.VALUE: If Union Square is your desired base of operations for your stay in San Francisco, the Sir Francis Drake offers some outstanding deals thourgh their online booking website. We were able to stay three nights for one-third the lowest rate offered by the Westin St. Francis just down the block. In this economy, that is a significant savings without giving up much in terms of luxury or amenities. LOCATION: You truly can't beat the location. a block up Powell Street from Union Square and all of the shopping that district has to offer. The cable cars stop right out in front of the hotel. The famous Dragon Gate entrance to Chinatown is walking distance four short blocks away.THE ROOMS: Ours was a 'Double Deluxe' with two very comfortable double beds. The room decor was very nice and fresh. The room itself was very clean and plenty large enough for my wife and I. Contrary to what others have written, the bathroom was every bit as large as you will find in most other three- and four-star hotels. If I were to have any concerns whatsoever about our room it was how few electrical outlets there were -- but I would only deem that a minor inconvenience.PEACE AND QUIET: Yes, the walls are somewhat thin and occasionally, we could hear the folks in the room next door trying to deal with their children. However, we did *not* hear the street noise others allude to. I suspect that is only an issue on rooms facing the street along the front of the building. Nor did we ever hear anything from the Starlight Room. Overall, it is a very quiet building for the most part.SERVICE: From the time we checked in and throughout our stay, every hotel staff member we interacted with was friendly and helpful. There was even a situation when we ran out of shampoo and called later in the evening to request an additional one from housekeeping. By this time, the housekeeping staff were not available, but in less than five minutes of calling guest services, shampoo was brought to our 7th-floor room by one of the building maintenance staff.FOOD: In addition to an excellent restaurant (Scala's Bistro) onsite, there are several dining options within a short walk. The famous Sears Fine Food restaurant (home of the Swedish pancakes) is directly across the street. Up on the corner is one of several downtown Lori's Diner locations. The Cheesecake factory is down the street atop Macy's Union Square store. Other eateries large and small abound.OTHER COMMENTS: Others had complained about slow and creaky elevators, but we rode all four and all were modern, quiet and efficient. Nothing to worry about there. We highly recommend the Sir Francis Drake and are planning to stay there again on our next visit to San Francisco.TRANSPORTATION TIP: If you are flying into San Francisco, skip the rental car unless you are going to be taking day trips outside of the city. Street parking is nearly non-existent and traffic tight in the central city and parking garages are expensive. Valet parking at the Sir Francis Drake was $44/day at the time of our visit. Instead, take BART (Pittsburg/Bay Point train) directly from the airport's international terminal to downtown (Powell Street station) and the hotel is 4½ blocks up Powell. Stop by the Muni tranit kiosk next to the cable car terminus and buy a Muni 1-day or 3-day passport for unlimited cable car, streetcar, metro and bus rides	
Jun 3 2008 	Location and Service	I stayed here for 2008 GDC (which was at the Moscone Center). It's a bit of a walk to there if you are not use to walking in a dense city. However, the location is great for everything. Plenty of restaurants and shopping (well, expensive shopping). Service was excellent. Little small, but that is what I expected. Don't expect to be able to see out of your window well either, but that wasn't an issue. The staff was top notch when I was there (sometimes these things change though). Let's just hit the bullets:Pros:- Location- Ambiance/Lobby- Good price for that Location and type of HotelCons:- Restaurant/Club overpriced.- Parking expensive (but you wouldn't need it anyways)	
