Jan 2 2008 	accentuate the positives...	My partner and I had the opportunity to stay at the Sir Francis Drake just after Christmas for three nights, where we were joined by my mother-in-law. The hotel is conveniently situated in the heart of Union Square, next to all the fantastic shopping that surrounds it. The hotel is charming from the beefeaters at the door, to the grand foyer and lobby. It is out of a different era.We had booked an Executive King for ourselves (room 925)and a regular Queen for the mother-in-law. Upon check-in, I was pleasantly surprised to see how big our room was. I believe that two rooms had merged to create a larger suite. The interior designers have had a lot of fun decorating the rooms. They are very unusual and kitschy, but at the same time stylish. Our room had a couch and chair, desk, king bed, bar fridge, tv, etc... all the usual touches. The only thing missing was an in-room safe and coffee maker.The bathroom was large with both a shower stall and a tub, but had a small vanity which made it hard to place all our bath products. The hotel supplies Aveda products so the quality was high. The bathroom decor fit the period style of the hotel, but was recently updated. There were a couple of problems with our room... the biggest being its location. All the executive kings face Powell Street, which you will soon find out to be a bustling thoroughfare that is busy from morning to midnight. The clang clang clang of the trollies and other street noise will most likely keep some guests up at night. (they offer earplugs at the front desk, which I took advantage of.) I wouldn't recommend this side of the hotel for people who can't handle street noise. And there are other noises beyond that... early morning garbage trucks... and drunks leaving the Starlight Room... One minor problem was the dirty windows in our room that you could hardly see out of... I am not kidding... it looked like years of dirt and dust... the windows in this room were still single pane, so this might be a reason for the noise, too.My favorite part about the room was the bed... It is very comfortable.My mother-in-law had a much smaller room on the back side of the building... and it seemed much quieter. This room was small by anyone's standards... with one of the most claustrophobic bathrooms I have ever seen. I kid you not, but you almost have to sit on the toilet to brush your teeth or do your makeup. You might have two square feet of leg room. I wouldn't recommend the queen room for more than one person... and never for a big person... There is no room to move.All in all we had a good stay. I would recommend making sure you get the right room for yourself. The executive king was great but there was the noise factor... I wouldn't want the smaller room. But if all you want is a good comfortable bed, then go for it. The SFD's location can't be beat, with everything at your doorstep and the staff is friendly.I would recommend this hotel, but with a few caveats... but I would stay here again if the price was right. I have stayed at other Kimpton hotels in the past and this one seems just a step below... but the hotel has a certain grandeur to it that you won't get in a boutique hotel. I would have given it four stars had it not been for the noise...	
