Aug 9 2007	Great location historical hotel but not luxury	The Drake’s high points are its location a ½ block off Union Square and the historical beauty of the hotel evident in the ornate lobby and dramatic exterior. Check-in was just fine and the staff was polite and professional. But who goes to a hotel to hang out in the lobby? We had a queen corner room on the 18th floor with a gorgeous view of Union Square and the Westin St. Francis. The bed was a comfy pillow top and the smallish bathroom with new porcelain and marble finishes had Aveda products and served its purpose. A large person may find the bathroom a bit cramped. Room served its purpose well in terms of sleeping and bathing accommodations, but found some of the finish work in the newly renovated rooms to be sloppy. You could tell that the interior painting was rushed as the detail work around the old windows and fixtures was sloppy and the carpet was coming up in a few places along the wall. The outside of the windows were incredibly dirty and the hallway to the room was dark and depressing. I suppose that some these flaws could be expected in an old hotel, but the missed details prevent the Drake from being a true place of luxury.	
