Feb 21 2006 	Great location!	We stayed at the Sir Francis Drake Feb. 15-20. The location was great! The rooms were small, but nice. Five of us were in town for a Coldwell Banker Conference. Three in our group shared a room. The room was a little small for three, so they asked for an upgrade. They got a larger room with a sofa bed and two bathrooms for $40 more per night! We took the cable car to Union Square &amp; Fisherman's Wharf. Just hopped on it right out front! I highly recommend the Golddust around the corner. Great Bar, live music, good time. The Starlight room has an amazing view of the city. It was a very romantic place. We had a wonderful meal in China Town at The House of Nan King. If it is your first time, the chef likes to order for you. I also suggest The Steps of Rome for Italian. The waiters dance with you if you say it's your birthday. The food is good &amp; a fun atmosphere!We didn't get to go to Alcatraz because the tours were sold out. Make a reservation!I loved San Francisco, I will be back! I would stay at the Sir Francis Drake again. It isn't the Ritz, but I didn't pay for the Ritz!	
Feb 19 2006	Superficially grand but scratch the surface...	.... and you find an old, poorly maintained place. My wife and I spent an evening at the SFD to catch a play down the street, just off Union Square. We'd had a nice post-theatre meal last year at the hotel restaurant, Scala's, and thought the hotel would be worth a try. The location is terrific - just off Union Square, on the cable car line, etc. We'd stayed at another Kimpton property in Boston and were impressed by the hip neo-classic styling in the rooms and the attitude of the place. Well, at the Drake, the look comes off like an old Hollywood starlet who's now getting by on cat food.  It has a beautiful old turn of the century lobby with some of Kimpton's signature touches - nouveau high-style furnishings, etc. - the stylistic elements of which repeat in the rooms, per Kimpton's &quot;formula&quot;. But it comes across as too formulaic here, and a band-aid on some real problems. Such as: paper-thin walls between the rooms; sooty windows; poor temperature control throughout the hotel (about 55º in the lobby on the chilly day, okay, but at their retro rooftop lounge, &quot;Harry Denton's Starlight Room&quot; it was also downright chilly - no budget for, say, a Home Depot thermostat?). Our bathroom had only a handicapped shower mounted at nose level - necessitating a crouch to get wet (we never requested this type of room, and the place was clearly not full). Above the shower stall, a hole in the wall covered by a rectangle of white plastic held in place by some old white fabric tape. (!) The hallways were renovated in a half-baked way: hip-ish light fixtures but depressing brown walls, beat up doors, and a vague rotting smell. We won't be returning soon - the Drake has potential to be a flashy retro hotel experience, but Kimpton needs to pump some serious dough into it to make it a liveable place again.	
Jan 30 2006	3rd Time Back!	This hotel is great! I stay here every year and wouldn't consider anywhere else. The staff is very friendly and helpful. I especially like it when the staff remembers you even though you come once a year. With all the people coming in and out who could remember a face. San Francisco has some of the best and if not the greatest places to eat. The hotels &quot;Cafe Espresso&quot; is great for a breakfast and lunch. There is also &quot;Sears Restaurant&quot; across the street from the hotel as well. I had breakfast,lunch and dinner there, need I say more. I highly recommend the &quot;Steamed Mussels&quot; for dinner. This property is the ideal location.	
Jan 26 2006	We came away totally satisfyed	Like others, we had some reservations about the mixed reviews about this hotel and didn't know what to expect; needless to say that the hotel completely exceeded our expectations. You can get a good deal from the discout internet sites like Hotwire. The service was courteous and professional, and unlike other hotels, which are cookie cutter copies of each other, Sir Francis Drake is distinctive and eclectic. Sure the hotel shows some of its age, especially in the bathrooms, but the first room we were in was well appointed and clean, with a large TV; although on the smaller side, anyone used to traveling in Europe and NYC will not feel uncomfortable. The air conditioner was in the window, but this was not obtrusive at all.We also dined at La Scala; great food and service and had a drink in the Starlight room, which offers one of the best views of the city in an exceedingly elegant setting. The service was superb; one evening we had some friends stay with us. We asked for a cot at 2am, but they gave a larger room with double beds at no extra cost.Finally, you can’t possibly beat this location; a block from Union Square and walking distance to Nob Hill and China town. Go ahead, try this place out!! You can probably get it between $70-90 a night on one of the discount websites.	
